{"questionId":"19583","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Using geometry software, Pedro draws a quadrilateral <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>ABCD</mtext></math>. <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>AB</mtext><mo>=</mo><mn>8</mn><mo> </mo><mtext>cm</mtext></math> and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>CD</mtext><mo>=</mo><mn>9</mn><mo> </mo><mtext>cm</mtext></math>. Angle <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>BAD</mtext><mo>=</mo><mn>51</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>°</mo></math> and angle <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>ADB</mtext><mo>=</mo><mn>52</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>°</mo></math>. This information is shown in the diagram.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/8dda9f59789003d94f7e251a0c49f5d4e2888bbe.png\"></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>CE</mtext><mo>=</mo><mn>7</mn><mo> </mo><mtext>cm</mtext></math>, where point <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>E</mtext></math> is the midpoint of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>BD</mtext></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Calculate the area of triangle <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>BDC</mtext></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><em><strong>Units are required in this question.</strong></em></p>\n<p><strong><br><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mtext>area</mtext><mo>=</mo></mrow></mfenced><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>×</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>89164</mn><mo>…</mo><mo>×</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>×</mo><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mn>48</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>°</mo></math>&nbsp;</strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<strong><em>(M1)(A1)</em>(ft)</strong></p>\n<p><em><strong><br></strong></em><strong>Note:</strong> Award <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em> for substituted area formula. Award <strong><em>(A1)</em></strong> for correct substitution.</p>\n<p><br><strong><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mtext>area</mtext><mo>=</mo></mrow></mfenced><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>26</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo> </mo><msup><mtext>cm</mtext><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>26</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>3908</mn><mo>…</mo></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp;</strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(A1)(ft)</strong></em><em><strong>(G3)</strong></em></p>\n<p><br><strong>Note:</strong> Follow through from part (a).</p>\n<p><em><strong><br></strong></em><em><strong>[3 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"19583","referenceCode":"20N.2.SL.TZ0.T_3c","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Calculate the area of triangle BDC.","paper":"2","level":"SL","questionNumber":"c","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 3]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.2—2d and 3d trig, sine rule, cosine rule, area"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}